Vaccinium uliginosum, commonly known as bog blueberry, is a deciduous shrub native to the Northern Hemisphere. 
It grows up to 1-2 meters tall and has thin, woody stems. 
The leaves are elliptical in shape, finely toothed, and an olive-green color with a glossy surface. 
The flowers are small and bell-shaped, white to pink in color. 
The fruit is a dark blue or black berry with a sweet and tart taste, often used for culinary purposes. 
Vaccinium uliginosum grows in wet, swampy areas, bogs, and heathlands. 
It is known for its high antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties and is sometimes used for medicinal purposes.
